from test: 21 The effect of the stress was studied by local electrochemical impedance spectroscopy in boric/borate aqueous electrolyte. It is possible to compare the impedance for the strained and non-strained areas. The carbon steel sample was strained using the constant load cell and the stress was controlled by a load sensor. The local impedance was monitored by performing a measurement at a single location at the center of notch simultaneously with the global impedance, which corresponds to an averaged value over the whole exposed surface to the electrolyte. Figure 5 shows that the load (300 MPa) increased the local capacitance from 2 to 3.4 μF/cm2. In first approximation, this increase of capacitance can be seen as a thinning of the passive film when increasing the mechanical stress. A similar effect can be the result of increasing the real surface of the working electrode, for instance due to increasing of the surface roughness.
from Soup: 21 The effect of the stress was studied by local electrochemical impedance spectroscopy in boric/borate aqueous electrolyte. It is possible to compare the impedance for the strained and non-strained areas. The carbon steel sample was strained using the constant load cell and the stress was controlled by a load sensor. The local impedance was monitored by performing a measurement at a single location at the center of notch simultaneously with the global impedance, which corresponds to an averaged value over the whole exposed surface to the electrolyte. Figure 5 shows that the load (300 MPa) increased the local capacitance from 2 to 3.4 μF/cm 2 . In first approximation, this increase of capacitance can be seen as a thinning of the passive film when increasing the mechanical stress. A similar effect can be the result of increasing the real surface of the working electrode, for instance due to increasing of the surface roughness.
